Russian Communism Makes a Comeback
Moscow—A Year Ago, During a Break from Teaching at an American University, I Returned to My Hometown of Moscow.
My destination wasn't some kind of bastion of free speech.
But there were still some remnants of freedom in this place.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny had traveled the country in an attempt to garner support for politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Public protests broke out.
Independent non-governmental organizations are operating domestically.
Journalists and analysts may not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely seen as a historical legacy.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protests he initiated have been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was disbanded for "extremism," while its members are facing exile or investigation.
Nearly every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agents" list — or worse, labeled as "undesirables."
Over the past year, Russia has plunged into a non-free state, though it's not far off and has been very intense.
For example, a law designating foreign agents was passed in 2012, aimed at destroying or defaming institutions or people that engage in "political activity" and receive funding from abroad.
However, this law has become increasingly arbitrary, with retweeting now being a reason to be labeled as a foreign agent.
（ "Undesirables" label will lead to a complete ban on you.
）In just one year, the number of entities added to the list of foreign agents has hit a record 101.
In total, 359 people and organizations are included, with 88 related to media.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed because they "affect the country's politics."
But the core goal of journalism and propaganda is of course to affect politics.
But this is exactly the problem: despite Vladimir Putin having positioned himself as the inevitable future controller of Russian politics, he views criticism as a survival threat.
Despite enduring all that silence and persecution, it's the Communist Party, an unlikely entity, that has managed to survive and become the only real opposition to the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy -- urging the public to support the forces most likely to defeat the Kremlin's candidates -- and the Communist Party's strong showing in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the State Duma vote, while the Kremlin-backed United Russia Party secured nearly 49.8%.
However, the Communists refuse to accept the result, insisting that the vote was rigged.
In fact, some experts estimate they should have received about 30% of the vote, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
To many Russians, communists seem to be more respected than Putin now.
But they're not the original communists.
They not only don't deny the joys of the world, but party members are actually wearing sheepskin coats, enthusiastic about traveling abroad, driving foreign cars and using social media.
Some are millionaires — like the charming head of agriculture, Pavel Grudinin (who was banned from participating in the election last month).
Although the party is still led by 77-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by young party members.
To take Nikola Bondaichenko as an example.
With the nickname "Red Navalny," 36-year-old Bondaichenko strongly criticized the terrible pension reform in 2018.
Recently, when a regional department head suggested that Russians should be able to "live better" on a monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (equivalent to $50), Bondaichenko recorded his efforts to prove him wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite the threat of being banned from running, Bondaichenko was still allowed to participate in the State Duma election last month.
Although he received support from Navalny's Smart Voting system, he still lost to the United Russia Party's candidate.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently came up with a title for a protest, accusing the "state and government" of "controlling" United Russia.
Then there's Anastasia Udodova, 43 years old.
Like Bondaichenko, she incredibly lost the last election.
But she remains very — and increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the Smart Voting system, another rising star,  Ekaterina Ngalychewa, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Interestingly, the Communist Party's modernization reflects people's nostalgia for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and a country that achieved these ideals, although strict, was still not lacking in justice and kindness.
Furthermore, like Navalny, today's Communists represent a predictable and consistent vision, in which a person's wild imagination would not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all Kremlin opponents are increasingly uniting: a "united Russia" has formed, which can be opposed to Putin's United Russia party.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš, also known as the Czech Donald Trump, failed to continue as prime minister as the opposition alliance set aside their ideological differences and formed a joint alliance, with its leader Petr Fiala possibly leading a new government along with another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People are fed up with populists," they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The Hungarian opposition will also draft a unified electoral list for next year's parliamentary elections and put up a joint candidate for prime minister.
Certainly, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
However, toppling Putin would be much more difficult, and it's not hard to predict that there will be more comprehensive measures to crush the Communist Party.
But the above actions also brought risks to the Kremlin.
Now the situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not disappeared," and points out that the country still has "an active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he is at least still interested in pretending that Russia is not being led towards near totalitarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia into an even more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin, like it did with Russian liberals, is repeatedly capricious in making and enforcing rules, thereby driving the Communist Party underground, then social explosions are more likely to occur.
But if it decides not to suppress it anymore, Russian Communists — — yes, that's right, Communists — — may become an irresistible force.
